Core Objectives & Strategy
Outcome Comparison: Determine if substituting SNF with Home Health negatively impacts clinical outcomes, such as 30/60/90-day readmission or admission rates.

Member Profiling: Identify which members are clinically appropriate for Home Health rather than SNF.

Accessibility Bias: Address the challenge that Home Health data is often skewed by provider availability rather than purely clinical need. This "accessibility" factor must be controlled in future regression analyses.

The "Personal Care Fund" Initiative
The team is evaluating a proposed Medicare benefit for members approved for SNF who prefer to receive care at home. The analysis will segment members into three groups based on claim and authorization data:

Group 1: Approved for SNF and admitted to SNF.

Group 2: Approved for SNF but went straight home with no SNF claim.

Group 3: Approved for SNF, went home, but were admitted to SNF after a lag period.

Data & Technical Requirements
Authorization Integration: Use "MNA" (Member Not Admitted) status to identify members who did not utilize their SNF authorization.

2025 Data Focus: The analysis will prioritize full-year 2025 data to ensure relevance.

Granular Metrics: Analysis will include "Episode of Care" definitions, Home Health duration, and total cost comparisons across different lines of business (Commercial, Medicare, D-SNP).
